[3] Ireland (Dublin)
Date: Fri 3 Aug 2018
Source: Lovin Dublin [edited]
https://lovindublin.com/news/hse-measles-dublin-august


Dubliners are being warned by the HSE [Health Service Executive; Ireland's national health service] to be extremely vigilant after it was confirmed that there had been 2 cases of measles in the capital. It was first confirmed 2 weeks ago [20 July 2018] that one adult and one child had been diagnosed, but the HSE has confirmed that there have been 4 more cases in Dublin. According to the HSE, these 4 individuals are likely to have developed measles from contact with one of the 2 earlier cases at hospitals in Dublin. The HSE is requesting people to continue to be vigilant about measles.

More than 35 people have died because of measles in Europe in 2018 according to the BBC. A spokesperson for the HSE said, "Measles is highly contagious and is spread easily. The time between exposure to measles and developing the rash is usually 14 days (range 7-21 days). People are infectious from 4 days before rash starts until 4 days after. Measles can cause chest infections, fits (seizures), ear infections, swelling of the brain and/or damage to the brain."

[byline: Darragh Berry]

