[5] North Korea -- elimination report
Date: Sun 4 Aug 2018
Source: Precision Vaccinations [edited]
https://www.precisionvaccinations.com/international-travelers-north-korea-should-verify-immunization-status-measles-japanese-encephalitis


In a significant win against an expanding disease, North Korea was verified for eliminating measles, announced the World Health Organization (WHO) in a press release. On 2 Aug 2018, the Regional Verification Commission verified that North Korea had interrupted transmission of indigenous measles for more than 3 years. In 2014, WHO South-East Asia announced the elimination of measles by 2020 as a flagship program.

In total, more than 16 million people living in North Korea were vaccinated for measles at a cost of approximately USD 6.3 million. The North Korea vaccination campaign came in rapid response to a significant measles outbreak that began in November 2006. The 1st cases in this outbreak were initially thought to be rubella, as measles had not been reported in North Korea since 1992, said WHO.

With today's [4 Aug 2018] WHO announcements, 4 of the 11 member countries of WHO South-East Asia have now eliminated measles. WHO is the lead technical agency responsible for coordination of immunization and surveillance activities supporting all countries to achieve the 2020 goal.

"This achievement by [North Korea] demonstrates the commitment and resolve of countries in the Region towards the health of women and children, and for universal health coverage", said Dr Poonam Khetrapal Singh, regional director WHO South-East Asia. Nearly 400 million children are planned to be vaccinated through mass campaigns with measles vaccine in 2018-2019 in the Region, said WHO. "We are moving towards a brighter and healthier future for all -- one that is free of vaccine-preventable diseases and the unnecessary death and suffering they cause," Dr Singh said.

In North Korea, measles was declared eliminated in 2006. However, a measles outbreak occurred in 2013. Most measles cases in South Korea have been associated with imported measles virus.

Current measles outbreaks are being reported throughout the EU, in South America and in various cities in the USA. In the USA, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) suggests visitors to North Korea ensure various immunizations are verified, including measles.

[byline: Don Ward Hackett]

